				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/sirius-moonlight" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1756721); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1756721&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610250884" alt="Sirius Moonlight" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1756721)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/sirius-moonlight" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1756721); return false;" >Sirius Moonlight</a></span> <span class="odate time_1383580030 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">04 Nov 2013 15:47</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1884909">
									

<p>I really enjoyed the series but one thing is bugging me&#8230;</p>
<blockquote>
<p>You must close the containment chamber. To ensure success, you must remain inside the chamber when it closes. The Foundation will honor your sacrifice and its meaning for the continued existence of the human race, but there is no chance of survival. We are sorry.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Why would it be necessary to remain inside the containment chamber to ensure success in closing the door? Who designs containment chambers like that? Sure, it makes the whole thing more poignant - the heroic self-sacrifice and all that - but it just seems like an unneccessary sacrifice.</p>
<p>Years ago I read an account of a sinking ship, and the sacrice made by sailors belowdecks to seal off a flooding section of the hull from within in order to try to save the ship. In this case the sacrifice really was required and it really was a poignant scene. But without that necessity (as in this story), it doesn't quite work, imho.</p>
<p>Still, +1 on the overall strength of it.</p>

							</div>

								
					
