			<div class="content" id="post-content-2699522">
									

<p>I realize this is potentially 3 years too late, But I just wanted to give my two cents on the subject.</p>
<p>It could be that the it was a typical &quot;hidden vault&quot;-type door, as in, the outside of the door is just a blank, featureless wall, but on the inside it is more of a proper door. If the door opened inward (as in: into the weird chamber), it would require that someone pushed the door closed from the inside.</p>
<p>It is also very similar to how the Pharaohs built the pyramids. The &quot;finishing touch&quot; was often that a couple of slaves were forced to seal the tombs from the inside, to guarantee that nobody would find a way to get in. Dead men tell no tales, after all.</p>

